SIMPLE: thief
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thief
<hw>Thief</hw> <pr>(th⟦emac⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Thieves</plw> <pr>(th⟦emac⟧vz)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE.
<ets>thef</ets>, <ets>theef</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧e⟦oacute⟧f</ets>;
akin to OFries. <ets>thiaf</ets>, OS. <ets>theof</ets>,
<ets>thiof</ets>, D. <ets>dief</ets>, G. <ets>dieb</ets>, OHG.
<ets>diob</ets>, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧j⟦omac⟧fr</ets>, Sw. <ets>tjuf</ets>,
Dan. <ets>tyv</ets>, Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧iufs</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧iubs</ets>, and perhaps to Lith. <ets>tupeti</ets> to squat
or crouch down. Cf. <er>Theft</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who
steals; one who commits theft or larceny. See <er>Theft</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There came a privy <qex>thief</qex>, men clepeth death.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where <qex>thieves</qex> break through and steal.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. vi. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A waster in the snuff of a candle.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thief catcher</b></col>. <cd>Same as <er>Thief
taker</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Thief leader</b></col>, <cd>one who leads or
takes away a thief.</cd> <au>L'Estrange.</au> -- <col><b>Thief
taker</b></col>, <cd>one whose business is to find and capture thieves
and bring them to justice.</cd> -- <col><b>Thief tube</b></col>, <cd>a
tube for withdrawing a sample of a liquid from a cask.</cd> --
<col><b>Thieves' vinegar</b></col>, <cd>a kind of aromatic vinegar for
the sick room, taking its name from the story that thieves, by using it,
were enabled to plunder, with impunity to health, in the great plague at
London.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Robber; pilferer.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Thief</er>, <er>Robber</er>. A <xex>thief</xex> takes our property
by stealth; a <xex>robber</xex> attacks us openly, and strips us by main
force.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take heed, have open eye, for <qex>thieves</qex> do foot by
night.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some roving <qex>robber</qex> calling to his fellows.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thiefly</ent>⟦br⟧
